  "theory": "NAT (Network Address Translation) is a technique that maps multiple private IP addresses to a single (or small pool of) public IP address(es), enabling an entire private network to share one public IP for internet connectivity.\n\nTypes of NAT:\n1. Static NAT: One-to-one mapping between private and public IP. Used when a private server needs a fixed public IP.\n2. Dynamic NAT: Many private IPs mapped to a pool of public IPs. No port modification.\n3. NAPT/PAT (Network Address Port Translation): Many-to-one. Multiple private hosts share one public IP using different port numbers. This is what most home routers do.\n\nNAPT/PAT Process:\nOutbound: Private packet arrives at router. Router creates a NAT entry: {Private IP:Port} → {Public IP:New Port}. Source IP:Port in the packet is rewritten to the public mapping. Packet is forwarded.\nInbound: Return packet arrives with Destination = Public IP:MappedPort. Router looks up the NAT table, finds the matching private IP:Port, rewrites the destination, and forwards to the LAN host.\n\nPrivate IP Ranges (RFC 1918):\n- 10.0.0.0/8 (Class A)\n- 172.16.0.0/12 (Class B)\n- 192.168.0.0/16 (Class C — most common in homes)\n\nAdvantages: Conserves IPv4 addresses; provides some security (hides internal topology).\nDisadvantages: Breaks end-to-end connectivity; incompatible with some protocols; adds latency.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "NAT maps private IPs (192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x, 172.16.x.x) to a single public IP.",
    "NAPT/PAT uses port numbers to distinguish multiple internal hosts on one public IP.",
    "NAT table: {Private IP:Port} ↔ {Public IP:Mapped Port} for each active connection.",
    "Outbound: router rewrites source IP:Port. Inbound: router rewrites destination IP:Port.",
    "Enables entire home/office LAN to share one ISP-assigned public IP address.",
    "NAT breaks end-to-end transparency — needs helpers like NAT traversal (STUN, TURN) for P2P."
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "Home and office routers sharing a single ISP-provided IP address.",
    "Enterprise networks isolating internal address space from the internet.",
    "IPv4 address conservation — delaying IPv6 adoption by multiplexing many hosts per public IP."
  ]
}
